(50, 'Western Civ - Renaissance', 'Valley', '{\"desc\":\"Made by schububu and Mr Carson&amp;amp;amp;#039;s notes, and probably chatgpt\",\"contnt\":{\"What were the independent city-states of Italy dominated by powerful families called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"communes\"]},\"What were the people at the bottom of the Italian social structure who did not experience the Renaissance called? (Peasants of Italy)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"popolo\"]},\"Who were the Italian mercenaries used by various communes to wage war?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"condottieri\"]},\"What was the governmental structure of the communes in which one man controls the government and passes that control down through his family?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"signori\"]},\"Who was the Renaissance author who wrote the Courtier, arguing that gentlemen should have a variety of skills to reach their full potential\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Balddassare Castiglione\",\"Bald\"]},\"Who was the historic head of the Medici family, who patroned the arts heavily?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lorenzo de Medici\"]},\"What was the system in which the rich commissioned artwork from the lower class to one up their buddies?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"patronage\"]},\"What was the work written by Niccol\\u00f2 Machiavelli on how self-centered humans are?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"The Prince\"]},\"Who was the author regarded as the father of humanism, and revived the use of Latin in literature?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Petrarch\"]},\"Who was the humanist author who wrote Utopia, a utopia satirizing the state of English society?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas Moore\",\"Moore\"]},\"Who was the Dutch, Christian scholar, who wrote The Education of a Christian Prince, and preached that Christian doctrine should guide all actions?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Desiderius Erasmus\",\"Erasmus\"]},\"Who invented the western printing press?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Johannes Gutenberg\",\"Gutenberg\"]},\"What was the movement that touted going against the church&#039;s authority and structure?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"anticlericalism\"]},\"Who was the Bohemian theologist, who led the Hussites, and created vernacular translations of the bible?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jan Hus\"]},\"Period from the 1560s to 1660s in which witchcraft trials increased in frequency because of the increasing divide between Protestantism and Roman Catholicism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Great Witch Hunt\"]},\"Who was the Florentine artistic genius who sculpted the Piet\\u00e0 and David in the style of classicism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Michelangelo\"]},\"Who was the architect and engineer who is most well known for creating the Dome of the Cathedral of Santa Maria? \":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Brunelleschi\"]},\"Who was the last of the three great artists of Renaissance Italy, who painted the School of Athens\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Raphael Santi\"]},\"Who was the famous engineer, architect, and artist who painted the Mona Lisa and the Last Supper\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Leonardo da Vinci\",\"da Vinci\",\"Vinci\"]},\"Who was the Venetian painter, who painted the Venus of Urbino and others depicting scenes from classical mythology combined with Christian doctrine, and founded mannerism.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Titian\"]},\"Who was the German painter and printmaker known for his great engraving skill?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Albrecht Durer\"]},\"Who was the Flemish painter and pioneer of oil painting during the Renaissance?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jan van Eyck\"]},\"Who were the European rulers who further centralized power and reduced noble and merchant influence by doing so?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"New Monarchs\"]},\"What was the period in which the popes resided in Avignon, France, enjoying the luxuries life had to offer?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Babylonian Captivity\"]},\"What was the period in which a large rise in inflation caused by discoveries from the New World and a large influx in silver and gold boolean?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Price Revolution\"]},\"What was the event when the Roman Catholic Church broke into many parts on account of a certain man (\\u3063 \\u00b0\\u0414 \\u00b0;)\\u3063 ?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"The Great Schism\",\"Great Schism\"]},\"Who was  a Franciscan friar who criticized the Church and believed the state and Church should separate, and created a philosophical concept called _____&#039;s razor that emphasized simple explanations?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"William of Occam\"]},\"Who was a critic of church leadership on account with disgust of clerical corruption, who believed the state and Church should work together with the Church subordinate?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Marsiglio of Padua\"]},\"Who was the English theologian who was denounced a heretic by the church because the created vernacular bible translations.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"John Wyclif\"]},\"What was the reform movement to address corruption and restore the church after the Great Schism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"concillarism\"]},\"What was the war focusing on the Holy Roman Empire, after which German states obtained the freedom to choose their state religion?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thirty Years War\"]},\"What ended the Thirty Years War?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Peace of Westphalia\"]},\"Who was the Venetian merchant who traveled across the Silk Road and recorded his travels in his famous book?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Marco Polo\"]},\"Who was the royal who advanced navigation and exploration, fostering the Age of Discovery in Portugal?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry The Navigator\"]},\"Who was the Christian reformer who believed the Scriptures were the only factual source of religious doctrine for worship?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas a Kempis\"]},\"Who started the Protestant revolution?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Martin Luther\"]},\"Who was the Swiss Protestant Leader who broke up with Luther over the Eucharist?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ulrich Zwingli\"]},\"Who were the radical protestants that vehemently went against everything the Roman Catholic Church stood for?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Anabaptists\"]},\"Who founded the Protestant Branch preaching predestination and God&#039;s sanctity?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"John Calvin\"]},\"What was the revolt in which peasants from Germany rose against the Catholic Church, which Luther notably did not support?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"German Peasants Revolt\"]},\"Who was the English ruler who split England from the Roman Catholic Church?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry VIII\"]},\"Who was the English ruler who took the middle road in terms of Religious reform and fought the Spanish Armada?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Elizabeth I\"]},\"Who was the English ruler, offspring of Henry VIII, who attempted to restore Catholicism during their short reign.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mary I\",\"Bloody Mary\"]},\"Who was the Protestant offspring of Henry VIII, who followed his father&#039;s religious reforms?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Edward VI\"]},\"What was the Catholic council (under Pope Paul III) dedicated to combating Protestants and re-affirming their beliefs of Catholicism while fixing poor Church practices?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Council of Trent\"]},\"What was the Protestant movement founded by Ignatius of Loyola, which initiated the counter-reformation\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jesuits\"]},\"Who was the guy who didn&#039;t like Luther and made him legally an outlaw?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Charles V\"]},\"What document allowed the German states to choose their state religion?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Peace of Augsburg\"]},\"What was the French Protestant minority which revolted and got rights?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Huguenots\"]},\"Who was the guy who became king after the wedding?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry IV\"]},\"Who was the Dutch Catholic king who tried to snuff out Catholicism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Philip II\"]},\"What was the legal entity that later became the Netherlands?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"United Provinces\"]},\"What was the fleet of 130 sheeps who failed to conquer England under Philip II?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Spanish Armada\"]},\"What was the political ideology that New Monarchs followed, under which to obtain power they did more politicking and economic tradewar than actual war?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mercantalism\"]},\"Who was humanist philosopher who wrote Oration on the Dignity of Man, on the unlimited potential of human nature when fully cultivated?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pico Della Mirandola\"]},\"An explorer who was funded by Spain, and discovered the North and South American continents.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Christopher Columbus\",\"Columbus\"]},\"A Florentine navigator who was the first person to suggest the possibility that the Americas were a new continent (the New World).\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Amerigo Vespucci\"]},\"The pope who passed the Treaty of Tordesillas, a treaty that divided the territories between Spain and Portugal to end the problems between the two.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pope Alexander VI\"]},\"A treaty that divided the territories between Spain and Portugal to end the problems between the two.\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Treaty of Tordesillas\"]},\"An explorer from Portugal who discovered Brazil while trying to get to India.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pedro \\u00c1lvares Cabral\",\"Pedro Alvares Cabral\"]},\"An explorer who was sent by Charles V and traveled around the world (while one of his ships managed to travel the whole world, he died during the journey).\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ferdinand Magellan\"]},\"A Genoese merchant who discovered Newfoundland while attempting to get to Brazil\\n\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"John Cabot\"]},\"An English explorer who sailed around a Canadian bay; brought back lots of ore but not many riches\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Martin Frobisher\"]},\"A French explorer who found the La China rapids while exploring a route to Asia.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jacques Cartier\"]},\"A Spanish conqueror who conquered the Mexican Empire (very brutal).\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hernando Cort\\u00e9s\",\"Hernado Corte\"]},\"A Spanish conqueror who conquered Incan civilization (also very brutal). \\n\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Francisco Pizarro\"]},\"An English colony; it mysteriously disappeared after 3 years and is still a mystery today.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Colony of Roanoke\",\"Roanoke\"]},\"Founded the first permanent French settlement at Quebec in 1608 (a year after Jamestown was founded). The French were great traders and explorers; reached many states.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Colony of Samuel de Champlain\",\"Champlain\"]},\"French explorer who descended the Mississippi in 1682 to the Gulf of Mexico, opening the way for French occupation of Louisiana.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ren\\u00e9-Robert Cavelier LaSalle\",\"Rob\"]}}}', '[2,1,14,8]', 1),
(51, 'Western Civilization Unit 4 - Early Modern Europe.', 'SeanO', '{\"desc\":\"\",\"contnt\":{\"Lorenzo de Medici\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Italian statesman, the de facto ruler of the Florentine Republic, and the most powerful patron of Renaissance culture in Italy.\"]},\"Humanism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"a doctrine, attitude, or way of life centered on human interests or values\"]},\"Secularism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"the belief that religion and religious considerations should be ignored\"]},\"Individualism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"the belief in the value and significance of each person, which encouraged artists to make their paintings more personalized.\"]},\"Classicism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"an intellectual movement that sought to mimic the literature, rhetoric, art, and philosophy of the ancient world, specifically ancient Rome.\"]},\"The Patronage System\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Rich people commissioned arts and stuff from artists as a way to flex on all of the brokies.\"]},\"The Prince\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nicollo Machiavelli&#039;s opinions on the way rulers should rule.\\u00a0 Rulers should be feared with lots of power.\"]},\"Thomas More\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"English lawyer, judge, social philosopher, author, statesman, amateur theologian, and noted Renaissance humanist who wrote the Utopia\\u00a0\"]},\"Erasmus\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Erasmus was a Dutch Christian humanist, Catholic priest and theologian, educationalist, satirist, and philosopher who translated the New Testament into latin\\u00a0and also an important figure in patristics and classical literature\"]},\"Johann Gutenberg\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Invented the printing press.\"]},\"Anticlericalism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Opposition to religious authority especially in politics.\"]},\"Great Witch Hunt\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"a surge in the number of accusations of witchcraft and witch trials \"]},\"Francisco Pizarro\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Spanish conqueror who conquered the Incans.\"]},\"Henry the Navigator\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Son of the King of Portugal who was a sailor who was a patron of voyages of discovery among the Madeira Islands and along the western coast of Africa\"]},\"Price Revolution\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"a period of rapid inflation and decline in the value of money in Europe from the late 15th century through the early and mid-17th century\"]},\"Bartolomeu Dias\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"First person to make it to the Cape of Good Hope, Portuguese sailor\"]},\"Ferdinand Magellan\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"First person to circumnavigate the globe, But he died in the Philippines by natives.\"]},\"Michelangelo\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"He was an Italian sculptor, painter, architect, and poet of the High Renaissance who created the David\\u00a0and the Creation of Adam.\"]},\"Brunelleschi\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"was an Italian architect, designer, goldsmith and sculptor. He is considered to be a founding father of Renaissance architecture.\"]},\"Raphael Santi\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Raphael Santi (1483\\u20131520) was an Italian Renaissance painter and architect, renowned for his harmonious and balanced compositions. His masterpieces, such as The School of Athens, exemplify his mastery of perspective, human form, and serene beauty, influencing Western art for centuries.\"]},\"Donatello\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Donatello (1386\\u20131466) was an Italian sculptor, renowned for his innovative work in Renaissance art, particularly his lifelike statues like Saint George.\"]},\"Leonardo da Vinci\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\" A Renaissance polymath, renowned for his art, science, and inventions, including masterpieces like Mona Lisa and The Last Supper.\"]},\"Albrecht D\\u00fcrer\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\" A German Renaissance artist known for his detailed woodcuts, engravings, and paintings, blending Northern European and Italian techniques.\"]},\"Jan van Eyck\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A Flemish painter known for his detailed oil paintings, such as The Arnolfini Portrait, which showcased advances in realism and color.\"]},\"New Monarchs\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"European rulers in the late 15th century who centralized power and reduced feudal influence, like Henry VII of England and Ferdinand and Isabella of Spain.\"]},\"Great Schism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"The division within the Catholic Church (1378-1417), where two, later three, rival popes claimed authority, weakening the church&#039;s unity.\"]},\"John Wyclif\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"An English theologian and reformer who criticized church practices and translated the Bible into English, laying the groundwork for Protestant Reformation.\"]},\"Thirty Years&#039; War (1618-1648)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A religious and political conflict in Europe, primarily between Catholic and Protestant states, resulting in widespread devastation and territorial changes.\"]},\"Jacques Cartier\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A French explorer who claimed parts of Canada for France in the 16th century, mapping the St. Lawrence River.\"]},\"Hern\\u00e1n Cort\\u00e9s\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A Spanish conquistador who led the conquest of the Aztec Empire in the early 16th century, bringing vast wealth to Spain.\"]},\"Vasco da Gama\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A Portuguese explorer who opened sea trade routes to India in the late 15th century, significantly impacting global commerce.\"]},\"Mercantilism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"An economic theory that emphasized the accumulation of wealth, primarily through a favorable balance of trade, and encouraged government regulation.\"]},\"Marco Polo\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A Venetian explorer who traveled to Asia and wrote about his experiences, sparking European interest in trade with the East.\"]},\"Martin Luther\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A German theologian who sparked the Protestant Reformation in 1517 by posting his 95 Theses, challenging the Catholic Church&#039;s practices, particularly the sale of indulgences.\"]},\"Anabaptists\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\" A radical Protestant sect in the 16th century that believed in adult baptism and separation from state control, influencing later Protestant denominations.\"]},\"John Calvin\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A French-born theologian who developed Calvinism, emphasizing predestination and the absolute sovereignty of God, significantly shaping Protestant thought.\"]},\"German Peasants Revolt\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A 1524-1525 uprising by German peasants demanding social and economic reforms, inspired by Martin Luther&#039;s ideas but ending in violent repression.\"]},\"Henry VIII\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"King of England (1509-1547) who broke from the Catholic Church and established the Church of England, primarily to secure his divorce from Catherine of Aragon.\"]},\"Elizabeth I\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Queen of England (1558-1603) who restored Protestantism, defeated the Spanish Armada, and presided over a period of cultural flourishing known as the Elizabethan Era.\"]},\"Mary I\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Queen of England (1553-1558) who attempted to restore Catholicism, earning the nickname &quot;Bloody Mary&quot; for her persecution of Protestants.\"]},\"Edward VI\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"King of England (1547-1553), son of Henry VIII, who pursued Protestant reforms but died young, leaving the throne to Mary I.\"]},\"Council of Trent\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A series of Catholic Church meetings (1545-1563) aimed at countering Protestantism, reforming church practices, and affirming Catholic doctrine.\"]},\"Jesuits\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A Catholic religious order founded by Ignatius of Loyola in 1540, focused on education, missionary work, and defending Catholicism during the Counter-Reformation.\"]},\"Peace of Augsburg\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A 1555 treaty that allowed German princes to choose between Catholicism and Lutheranism for their territories, temporarily ending religious conflict in the Holy Roman Empire.\"]},\"Huguenots\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"French Protestants, largely followers of John Calvin, who faced severe persecution in Catholic France, culminating in events like the St. Bartholomew&#039;s Day Massacre.\"]},\"Philip II\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"King of Spain (1556-1598), a staunch Catholic ruler who fought against Protestantism, including the failed Spanish Armada against England in 1588.\"]},\"Spanish Armada\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A fleet sent by Philip II of Spain in 1588 to invade England, which was decisively defeated, marking a turning point in European naval power.\"]},\"Christopher Columbus\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"An Italian explorer who, under Spanish patronage, made landfall in the Americas in 1492, opening the New World to European exploration and colonization.\"]}}}', '[14,2,1]', 1);
INSERT INTO `decks` (`id`, `name`, `owner`, `data`, `viewdata`, `public`) VALUES
(52, 'Western Civ - S1 Finals', 'Valley', '{\"desc\":\"All my previous decks for this semester, put together\",\"contnt\":{\"Which empire based their power in the cities of Tyre and Sidon, built a mercantile empire, and founded colonies in Africa, Spain, and Sicily?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Phoenician\"]},\"Which empire settled in Canaan, battled the Philistines, and developed ethical monotheism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hebrew\"]},\"Which empire developed a high-tech military, centralized political government, and built a large library?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Assyrian\"]},\"Which empire conquered judah, made Babylon their preak city, and was overthrown by rebels from Persia?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Chaldean\"]},\"Which empire had Zoroastrianism as their state religion, overthrew the Chaldeans, consolodated control to a central government?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Persian\"]},\"Which empire was made up of many city states, developed the wirst written alphabet, and developed the Epic of Gilgamesh?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sumerian\"]},\"Which empire built the world&#039;s first standing army, turned the city of Akkad into a center of trade, and expanded influence under Sargon the Great?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Akkadian\"]},\"Which empire was founded in Babylon after the Akkadian collapse and reached its peak under Hammurabi?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Amorite\"]},\"Which empire had history divided into Kingdoms,  Intermediate Periods, had growth facilitated by fertile silt, and whose rulers maintained ma&#039;at?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Egyptian\",\"Egypt\"]},\"Which empire was established in Anatolia, warred frequently with the Egyptians, and developed Iron Smelting?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hittite\"]},\"Who expanded the influence of the Akkadian Empire and built the worlds first standing army?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sargon the Great\"]},\"Who created the first written law code?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hammurabi\"]},\"Who was the famous female pharaoh that expanded Egypt&#039;s trade and built important stuff?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hatshepsut\"]},\"Who was the pharaoh that tried to impose monotheism upon Egypt?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Akhenaten\"]},\"Who was the pharaoh that built up the Egyptian empire by conquering the Medditeranean Coast?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Rhamses II\"]},\"Who led the Hebrews out of Egypt?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Moses\"]},\"Who set up the united kingdom of Isreal?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Moses\"]},\"What did Isreal experience under David and Solomon?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Golden Age\"]},\"Who was the ruler of Isreal known for their military conquest?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"David\"]},\"Whose son promoted trade and built an important temple for Isreal?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Solomon\"]},\"Who was the god that the Hebrew&#039;s worshiped?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Yaweh\"]},\"What did Tiglath-Pileser II and Sargon II do for Assyria?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Conquered\"]},\"Under who did the Chaldean empire peak? (absolute chad)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nebuchadnezzar II\"]},\"Who is the god of Zoroastrianism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ahura Mazda\"]},\"Who caused the Persian empire to adopt Zoroastrianism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Darius I\"]},\"What was the branch of monotheism that the Hebrews created?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ethical Monotheism\"]},\"What was the pact between God and the Hebrews?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Covenant\"]},\"What was the religious text developed by the Judah&#039;s citizens when they were exiled to Babylon?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Torah\"]},\"What was the river that stimulated the growth of the Egyptians?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nile\"]},\"What was the concept of harmony and justice that permeates the universe?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"ma&#039;at\",\"maat\"]},\"What was the first written language developed under the Sumerians?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Cuneiform\"]},\"What were the stepped pyramids that the Sumerians developed?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ziggurat\"]},\"What was the Sumerian story which detailed the search for Immortality?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Epic of Gilgamesh\"]},\"What was the battle that led to a peace treaty between the Hittites and Egyptians?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Battle of Kadesh\",\"Kadesh\"]},\"What was the Egyptian work that detailed a guide about how to be a good dead person?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Book of the Dead\"]},\"What was the name of a Persian local government official?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Satrap\"]},\"Who was the ancient Greek poet known for writing Theogony and Works and Days?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hesiod\"]},\"Who was the tyrant that seized power and established peace in Athens?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pisistratus\"]},\"What were the name of the heavily armed foot soldiers of Ancient Greece that played an essential role in phalanxes?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hoplites\"]},\"Who was the king of Macedon who united most of Greece, preparing the kingdom for his sons rule?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Philip II of Macedon\",\"Philip II\"]},\"Who is often called the Father of History and authored the History of the Persian wars?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Herodotus\"]},\"Who was the ancient Greek historian who wrote about the Peloponnesian War?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thucydides\"]},\"Who is known as the Father of Geometry and wrote the Elements, an influential geometry textbook?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Euclid\"]},\"Who was the ancient Greek philosopher sentenced to death for impiety and corrupting youth, and created a novel method of discussion?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Socrates\"]},\"Who was the ancient Greek mathematician and Astronomer that measured the circumference of the Earth?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Eratosthenes\"]},\"Which ancient Greek mathematician made significant contributions to geometry and mechanics, and discovered the principle of buoyancy?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Archimedes\"]},\"What was the earliest civilization on the Balkan Peninsula, that developed linear-a?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Minoan\"]},\"Who was the Athenian statesman credited with laying the foundations for democracy in Athens?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Solon\"]},\"What term describes a form of government where power is in the hands of a few?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Oligarchy\"]},\"What was the public open space in ancient Greek cities used for trade and civic duties?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Agora\"]},\"What term refers to the fortified hilltop found in many ancient Greek cities?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Acropolis\"]},\"Who was the ancient Greek playwright known for his tragedies, including Oedipus Rex?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sophocles\"]},\"Which playwright is considered the father of New Comedy in Ancient Greece?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Menander\"]},\"Who was the philosopher, student of Socrates, that founded the Academy in Athens authored The Republic, and developed The Theory of Forms?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Plato\"]},\"Which ancient Greek astronomer proposed that the Earth orbits the sun, a heliocentric view?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aristarchus\"]},\"What philosophy teaches that pleasure is the highest good, but advocates moderation?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Epicureanism\"]},\"What was the warlike Greek Civilization during the Bronze Age that supported Artisans, and had fortified towns like Argos.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mycenaean\"]},\"Which reformer is credited with establishing the foundations of Athenian democracy?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Cleisthenes\"]},\"What term refers to the rule by one who seized power unconstitutionally in ancient Greece?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Tyranny\"]},\"What term refers to the urban center of ancient Greek city-states?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Asty\"]},\"What term refers to the rural territory surrounding an ancient Greek city-state?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Chora\"]},\"Who was the great tragedian that wrote the Oresteia, a trilogy about a royal family falling from grace?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aeschylus\"]},\"Who was the prominent and influential statesman of Athens during its Golden Age?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pericles\"]},\"Which philosopher, a student of Plato, created the Lyceum, and tutored Alexander the Great?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aristotle\"]},\"Who is often regarded as the Father of Medicine, he also notably performed ethical medical treatments?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hippocrates\"]},\"Which philosophy advocates rationality and self-control as the means to achieve inner peace?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Stoicism\"]},\"Who was the ancient Greek poet known for composing the epic poems Iliad and Odyssey?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Homer\"]},\"Which Athenian lawmaker was known for his harsh legal code in the 7th century BCE? (He has an English word named after him)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Draco\"]},\"What form of government is characterized by rule by the people, often through elected representatives?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Democracy\"]},\"What was the term for the state-owned serfs in ancient Sparta?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Helot\"]},\"What was the popular assembly of citizens that held the greatest power in Athenian government called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ecclesia\"]},\"Which ancient Greek tragedian wrote plays such as Medea and The Bacchae?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Euripides\"]},\"Which ancient Greek playwright was known for his comedies, including The Clouds and Lysistrata?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aristophanes\"]},\"What were the professional teachers and philosophers in Ancient Greece who questioned traditional beliefs to gain greater understanding called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sophists\"]},\"What term refers to the early Greek philosophers who preceded Socrates and focused on natural phenomena?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pre-Socratics\",\"Presocratics\"]},\"Who was the Roman poet famous for writing the Metamorphoses and the Art of Love?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ovid\"]},\"Which Roman poet is known for his lyric poetry, including Odes and Satires?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Horace\"]},\"Who was the Roman general who defeated Hannibal in the Second Punic War, and pacified Spain for Rome?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Scipio Africanus\"]},\"Who was the early Christian missionary and apostle who spread Christianity across the Roman Empire?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Paul\"]},\"Who was the legendary founder and first king of Rome?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Romulus\"]},\"Which Roman general who commanded troops under Sulla joined the First Triumvirate?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pompey\"]},\"Who was the wealthy Roman politician and member of the First Triumvirate?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Crassus\"]},\"Which Roman emperor is infamous for his tyrannical rule, said to have burned Rome, and murdered his mom?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nero\"]},\"What was the elite unit of the Roman army that served as the bodyguards of the emperor\\u00a0 and played an important political role in Rome?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Praetorian Guard\"]},\"Who was the Roman orator, philosopher, and politician that wrote On Duties, and On Old Age?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Cicero\"]},\"Which Roman emperor made Christianity the official state religion of the Roman Empire?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Theodosius I\"]},\"Who was the Carthaginian general famous for crossing the Alps with war elephants during the Second Punic War?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hannibal Barca\",\"Hannibal\"]},\"Who is the central figure of Christianity, believed to be the son of God by Christians?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jesus of Nazareth\",\"Jesus\"]},\"What term refers to the wealthy, aristocratic class of ancient Rome?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Patricians\"]},\"Who was the Roman general who became dictator for life before being assassinated in 44 BCE, crossed the Rubicon, and conquered Gaul?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Julius Caesar\",\"Caesar\"]},\"Who was the Roman general and lover of Cleopatra, who fought against Octavian?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mark Antony\"]},\"Which Roman emperor is known for his philosophical writings, especially the Meditations, and was a stoic?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Marcus Aurelius\"]},\"What were the large military units of the Roman army called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Legions\",\"Legion\"]},\"Who was the Roman historian known for his extensive history of Rome, Ab Urbe Condita, which he was paid by Augustus to write?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Livy\"]},\"Which Roman emperor legalized Christianity with the Edict of Milan in 313 CE?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Constantine\"]},\"What civilization heavily influenced the early Romans before they gained independence?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Etruscans\"]},\"Who was the first Roman emperor who established the Pax Romana?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Octavian\",\"Augustus\"]},\"What term refers to the commoner class in ancient Rome?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Plebeians\"]},\"What was the long struggle between plebeians and patricians for political equality in ancient Rome?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Struggle of the Orders\"]},\"Which Roman emperor expanded the empire to its greatest extent, led Rome to victory against the Parthians, and built a new Roman Forum?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Trajan\"]},\"Who was the Roman poet who wrote the epic poem Aeneid?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Virgil\",\"Vergil\"]},\"Which Roman reformer was killed for attempting land reforms for the poor?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Tiberius Gracchus\",\"Gaius Gracchus\",\"Gracchus Brothers\",\"Gracchus\"]},\"Which Roman philosopher and playwright was a tutor to Nero, and believed in Stoicism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Seneca\"]},\"Who was the Roman historian known for his works Germania and Annals?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Tacitus\"]},\"What term describes the system of mutual obligations between powerful Roman political elites and people who provide votes in exchange for politcal sway?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Patron Client System\",\"Patron-Client System\",\"Patron Clien\"]},\"What was the highest elected political office in the Roman Republic, held by two individuals?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Consul\"]},\"What was the elected official in ancient Rome who represented the interests of the plebeians?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Tribune\",\"Tribune of the Plebs\",\"Tribune of the Plebeians\"]},\"What was the supreme governing body of ancient Rome, initially composed of aristocrats?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Senate\"]},\"Which Roman emperor is known for building a wall across Britain to keep out invaders, and being a patron of the arts?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hadrian\"]},\"Who was the Roman general and politician who reformed the army and was elected consul seven times?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Marius\"]},\"What was the Roman electoral body that could pass laws, and appoint Consuls, but relied on the Senate?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Centuriate\"]},\"Who were the people living in Sparta, who were free but only had partial citizenship?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Perioikoi\"]},\"Who set up a military dictatorship in Sparta?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lycurgus\"]},\"Who was the Greek Philosopher that believed water is the basic element of the universe?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thales\"]},\"What were the close-knit religious groups, that worshiped a certain god, and preached that hidden knowledge would bring them salvation?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mystery Cults\"]},\"What was the term for the male head of the household in the Imperial Roman Empire?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pater Patriae\"]},\"What was the term for worship of the emperor and the Roman state?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Roma et Augustus\"]},\"Who was the pope who set standards for papal responsibilities and missions, and protected Rome&#039;s food supply?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Gregory I\"]},\"Who expanded French territories and centralized royal power in France?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Philip II Augustus\",\"Philip II\"]},\"What term refers to sacred objects linked to saints, believed to offer divine connection?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Relic\",\"Relics\"]},\"What was the term for land on a manor retained by the lord and worked by peasants?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Demesne\"]},\"What were church officials interacting with the laity, administering sacraments without monastic vows?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Secular Clergy\"]},\"Who were clerics living under monastic rules in isolated communities dedicated to prayer and study?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Regular Clergy\"]},\"What was the eastern continuation of the Roman Empire known for its Orthodox Christianity?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Byzantine Empire\",\"Byzantine\"]},\"What legal code, commissioned by Justinian, influenced European law by codifying Roman principles?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Code of Justinian\"]},\"What was the period of cultural revival in France under Charlemagne, under which monks and secular clergy were educated in Latin?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Carolingian Renaissance\"]},\"What cultural period in northern England saw the creation of works like the Lindisfarne Gospels and an extensive library?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Northumbrian Renaissance\",\"Northumbrian\"]},\"Who was a Dominican theologian and scholastic, known for merging faith with Aristotelian philosophy?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas Aquinas\"]},\"What term refers to religious wars initiated by Christian states to reclaim the Holy Land?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Crusades\"]},\"What was the period of food shortages and starvation in early 14th-century Europe, caused by a little ice age and torrential rainstorms?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Great Famine\"]},\"What term describes the primary agrarian labor force, working land under lordly control?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Peasantry\",\"Serfs\",\"Peasants\",\"Peasant\"]},\"What was a grant by the Church reducing time spent in Purgatory, often obtained through donations?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Indulgence\"]},\"Who was the Muslim leader known for reclaiming Jerusalem from the Crusaders in 1187?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Saladin\"]},\"Who translated the Bible into Latin, creating the Vulgate and promoting classical studies?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"St. Jerome\",\"Jerome\"]},\"What is the term for land granted by a lord to a vassal in return for loyalty and service?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Fief\"]},\"Who were officials overseeing church districts called dioceses, with both spiritual and administrative power?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Bishop\"]},\"What is the office of the Pope, claiming supremacy over all Christians?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Papacy\"]},\"What religious life involves individuals withdrawing from society for ascetic living and prayer?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Monasticism\"]},\"What was an association controlling craft and trade standards in medieval towns, often made by traveling merchants and artisans?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Rowen Trading\",\"Guild\"]},\"What was the early Frankish dynasty founded by Clovis I who converted the Franks to Roman Catholic Christianity? \":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Merovingian Dynasty\",\"Merovingian\"]},\"Which Frankish dynasty reached its height under Charlemagne, known for cultural and military achievements, and was formed using marriage alliances by Pippin I?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Carolingian Dynasty\",\"Carolingian\"]},\"Who was the Frankish king and Holy Roman Emperor who united much of Western Europe?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Charlemagne\"]},\"What intellectual movement merged Christian doctrine with classical philosophy in medieval universities?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Scholasticism\"]},\"What architectural style in medieval Europe is known for its flying buttresses, stone ribbed roofs connected by plaster, and stained glass?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Gothic Architecture\",\"Gothic\"]},\"What term describes the land-owning and military elite in medieval European society?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nobility\",\"Nobles\"]},\"What is the transitional afterlife stage where souls are purified before entering heaven?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Purgatory\"]},\"Who was the Norman ruler who conquered England in 1066, centralizing power under a feudal system?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"William I \",\"William The Conqueror\",\"William the Great\",\"William the Bastard\",\"William\",\"Will\",\"Willy\",\"Willister\",\"Bill\",\"Billy\",\"Billford\",\"Billiam\"]},\"What social system involved lords granting land to vassals in exchange for loyalty and service?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Feudalism\"]},\"What economic system structured medieval estates, with peasants working land for their lords?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Manorialism\"]},\"What is the term for a church district overseen by a bishop, organizing Christian communities?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Diocese\"]},\"What set of guidelines created by a 6th-century saint regulated monastic life?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Rule of St. Benedict\",\"St. Benedict\"]},\"Who was the theologian from North Africa influential in Christian doctrine, especially on grace and human will through works such as The City of God?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Augustine of Hippo\"]},\"What was the Muslim kingdom in the Iberian Peninsula, known for its cultural and scientific exchange with Europe?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"al-Andalus\"]},\"Who was the Prophet and founder of Islam, central to the religion\\u2019s teachings in the Quran?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Muhammad\"]},\"What are the core practices of Islam, including faith, prayer, almsgiving, fasting, and pilgrimage?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Five Pillars of Islam\",\"Five Pillars\",\"5 Pillars\"]},\"Who were Norse seafarers known for their raids and trades, affecting Europe in the medieval period?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Vikings\"]},\"What were centers of higher learning in medieval Europe that evolved from cathedral and monastery schools?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Universities\"]},\"What was the pandemic in the 14th century that caused mass mortality and major social upheaval?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Black Death\"]},\"What was the prolonged conflict between England and France, resulting in great nationalism, development of parliament, and French land gains?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hundred Years War\",\"100 Years War\"]},\"Who were the religious leaders of the laity and caretakers of spiritual and church matters?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Clergy\"]},\"What was a coalition of German tribes called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Confederacy\"]},\"What were war bands of tribes called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Comitatus\"]},\"What were the independent city-states of Italy dominated by powerful families called?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"communes\"]},\"What were the people at the bottom of the Italian social structure who did not experience the Renaissance called? (Peasants of Italy)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"popolo\"]},\"Who were the Italian mercenaries used by various communes to wage war?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"condottieri\"]},\"What was the governmental structure of the communes in which one man controls the government and passes that control down through his family?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"signori\"]},\"Who was the Renaissance author who wrote the Courtier, arguing that gentlemen should have a variety of skills to reach their full potential\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Balddassare Castiglione\",\"Bald\"]},\"Who was the historic head of the Medici family, who patroned the arts heavily?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lorenzo de Medici\"]},\"What was the system in which the rich commissioned artwork from the lower class to one up their buddies?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"patronage\"]},\"What was the work written by Niccol\\u00f2 Machiavelli on how self-centered humans are?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"The Prince\"]},\"Who was the author regarded as the father of humanism, and revived the use of Latin in literature?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Petrarch\"]},\"Who was the humanist author who wrote Utopia, a utopia satirizing the state of English society?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas Moore\",\"Moore\"]},\"Who was the Dutch, Christian scholar, who wrote The Education of a Christian Prince, and preached that Christian doctrine should guide all actions?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Desiderius Erasmus\",\"Erasmus\"]},\"Who invented the western printing press?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Johannes Gutenberg\",\"Gutenberg\"]},\"What was the movement that touted going against the church&#039;s authority and structure?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"anticlericalism\"]},\"Who was the Bohemian theologist, who led the Hussites, and created vernacular translations of the bible?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jan Hus\"]},\"Period from the 1560s to 1660s in which witchcraft trials increased in frequency because of the increasing divide between Protestantism and Roman Catholicism\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Great Witch Hunt\"]},\"Who was the Florentine artistic genius who sculpted the Piet\\u00e0 and David in the style of classicism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Michelangelo\"]},\"Who was the architect and engineer who is most well known for creating the Dome of the Cathedral of Santa Maria? \":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Brunelleschi\"]},\"Who was the last of the three great artists of Renaissance Italy, who painted the School of Athens\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Raphael Santi\"]},\"Who was the famous engineer, architect, and artist who painted the Mona Lisa and the Last Supper\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Leonardo da Vinci\",\"da Vinci\",\"Vinci\"]},\"Who was the Venetian painter, who painted the Venus of Urbino and others depicting scenes from classical mythology combined with Christian doctrine, and founded mannerism.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Titian\"]},\"Who was the German painter and printmaker known for his great engraving skill?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Albrecht Durer\"]},\"Who was the Flemish painter and pioneer of oil painting during the Renaissance?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jan van Eyck\"]},\"Who were the European rulers who further centralized power and reduced noble and merchant influence by doing so?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"New Monarchs\"]},\"What was the period in which the popes resided in Avignon, France, enjoying the luxuries life had to offer?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Babylonian Captivity\"]},\"What was the period in which a large rise in inflation caused by discoveries from the New World and a large influx in silver and gold boolean?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Price Revolution\"]},\"What was the event when the Roman Catholic Church broke into many parts on account of a certain man?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"The Great Schism\",\"Great Schism\"]},\"Who was  a Franciscan friar who criticized the Church and believed the state and Church should separate, and created a philosophical concept called _____&#039;s razor that emphasized simple explanations?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"William of Occam\",\"Occam\"]},\"Who was a critic of church leadership on account with disgust of clerical corruption, who believed the state and Church should work together with the Church subordinate?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Marsiglio of Padua\"]},\"Who was the English theologian who was denounced a heretic by the church because the created vernacular bible translations.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"John Wyclif\"]},\"What was the reform movement to address corruption and restore the church after the Great Schism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"concillarism\"]},\"What was the war focusing on the Holy Roman Empire, after which German states obtained the freedom to choose their state religion?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thirty Years War\"]},\"What ended the Thirty Years War?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Peace of Westphalia\"]},\"Who was the Venetian merchant who traveled across the Silk Road and recorded his travels in his famous book?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Marco Polo\"]},\"Who was the royal who advanced navigation and exploration, fostering the Age of Discovery in Portugal?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry The Navigator\"]},\"Who was the Christian reformer who believed the Scriptures were the only factual source of religious doctrine for worship?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas a Kempis\"]},\"Who started the Protestant revolution?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Martin Luther\"]},\"Who was the Swiss Protestant Leader who broke up with Luther over the Eucharist?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ulrich Zwingli\"]},\"Who were the radical protestants that vehemently went against everything the Roman Catholic Church stood for?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Anabaptists\"]},\"Who founded the Protestant Branch preaching predestination and God&#039;s sanctity?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"John Calvin\"]},\"What was the revolt in which peasants from Germany rose against the Catholic Church, which Luther notably did not support?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"German Peasants Revolt\"]},\"Who was the English ruler who split England from the Roman Catholic Church?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry VIII\"]},\"Who was the English ruler who took the middle road in terms of Religious reform and fought the Spanish Armada?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Elizabeth I\"]},\"Who was the English ruler, offspring of Henry VIII, who attempted to restore Catholicism during their short reign.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mary I\",\"Bloody Mary\"]},\"Who was the Protestant offspring of Henry VIII, who followed his father&#039;s religious reforms?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Edward VI\"]},\"What was the Catholic council (under Pope Paul III) dedicated to combating Protestants and re-affirming their beliefs of Catholicism while fixing poor Church practices?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Council of Trent\"]},\"What was the Protestant movement founded by Ignatius of Loyola, which initiated the counter-reformation\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jesuits\"]},\"Who was the guy who didn&#039;t like Luther and made him legally an outlaw?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Charles V\"]},\"What document allowed the German states to choose their state religion?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Peace of Augsburg\"]},\"What was the French Protestant minority which revolted and got rights?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Huguenots\"]},\"Who was the guy who became king after the wedding, and subsequent event,  St. Bartholomew&#039;s Day Massacre?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry IV\"]},\"Who was the Dutch Catholic king who tried to snuff out Catholicism?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Philip II\"]},\"What was the legal entity that later became the Netherlands?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"United Provinces\"]},\"What was the fleet of 130 sheeps who failed to conquer England under Philip II?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Spanish Armada\"]},\"What was the political ideology that New Monarchs followed, under which to obtain power they did more politicking and economic tradewar than actual war?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mercantalism\"]},\"Who was humanist philosopher who wrote Oration on the Dignity of Man, on the unlimited potential of human nature when fully cultivated?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pico Della Mirandola\"]},\"An explorer who was funded by Spain, and discovered the North and South American continents.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Christopher Columbus\",\"Columbus\"]},\"The pope who passed the Treaty of Tordesillas, a treaty that divided the territories between Spain and Portugal to end the problems between the two.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pope Alexander VI\",\"Alexander VI\"]},\"A treaty that divided the territories between Spain and Portugal to end the problems between the two.\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Treaty of Tordesillas\",\"Treaty of Tortillas\"]},\"An explorer who was sent by Charles V and traveled around the world (while one of his ships managed to travel the whole world, he died during the journey).\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ferdinand Magellan\",\"Magellan\"]},\"What was the type of Medieval monasticism in which monks or nuns lived as hermits, inspired by St. Anthony of Egypt?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Eremetic Monasticism\",\"Eremetic\"]},\"What was the type of Medieval monasticism in which monks or nuns lived in organized communities, formalized by people such as St. Benedict?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Cenobitic Monasticism\",\"Cenobitic\"]}}}', '[2,10,20,3,14,1,19,22,5]', 1),
(53, 'AP CS A (S1) Vocab', 'Valley', '{\"desc\":\"Credit to Lucas for compiling the terms, and chatGPT for jsonifying them\",\"contnt\":{\"A person who designs, develops, and tests software for home, school, and business use\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Software engineer\"]},\"Consists of the class keyword and the name of the class\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Class header\"]},\"A text note to explain or annotate the code and is ignored when the program is run\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Comment\"]},\"A collection of programming commands\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Source code\"]},\"The rules for how a programmer must write code for a computer to understand\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Syntax\"]},\"A mistake in the code that does not follow a programming language&#039;s syntax\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Syntax error\"]},\"A characteristic of an object\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Attribute\"]},\"An action that an object can perform\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Behavior\"]},\"A programmer-defined blueprint from which objects are created\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Class\"]},\"An instance of a class\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Object\"]},\"An approach to creating and using models of physical or imagined objects\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Object-oriented programming\"]},\"A block of code that has the same name as the class and tells the computer how to create a new object\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Constructor\"]},\"To call the constructor to create an object\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Instantiate\"]},\"Used to call a method in a class\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Dot operator\"]},\"A named set of instructions to perform a task\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Method\"]},\"The specific value provided when a method or constructor is called\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Argument\"]},\"Defines the type of value to receive when a method or constructor is called\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Parameter\"]},\"A sequence of characters enclosed in quotation marks ( &quot; &quot; )\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"String literal\"]},\"A finite set of instructions that accomplish a task\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Algorithm\"]},\"Determines whether or not to execute a block of code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Condition\"]},\"A control structure that repeatedly executes a block of code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Iteration statement\"]},\"An object-oriented programming principle where a subclass inherits the attributes and behaviors of a superclass\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Inheritance\"]},\"A class that extends a superclass and inherits its attributes and behaviors\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Subclass\"]},\"A class that can be extended to create subclasses\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Superclass\"]},\"The class that contains the main method and from where the program starts running\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Tester class\"]},\"Consists of a name and parameter list\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Method signature\"]},\"To exit a method and go back to the point in the program that called it with the requested value or information\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Return\"]},\"The value returned before a method completes its execution and exits\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Return type\"]},\"Specifies that a method should not have a return value\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Void\"]},\"The process of examining code and providing feedback to improve the quality and functionality of the program\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Code review\"]},\"An operation which saves the latest changes of the code and represents a snapshot of a project\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Commit\"]},\"Written descriptions of the purpose and functionality of code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Documentation\"]},\"A set of guidelines and best practices for formatting program code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Programming style\"]},\"A statement that only executes when a condition is true\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Selection statement\"]},\"The format of the data that can be stored in a variable\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Data type\"]},\"Giving a name and data type to a variable\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Declaration\"]},\"A container that stores a value in memory\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Variable\"]},\"The process of breaking a problem down into smaller parts to write methods for each part\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Decomposition\"]},\"Getting the best outcome with the least amount of waste\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Efficient\"]},\"A plain language description of the steps in an algorithm\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pseudocode\"]},\"Code that is unnecessary\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Redundant\"]},\"An operator that returns a Boolean value\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Logical operator\"]},\"Specifies a block of code to execute when the condition is true and a block of code to execute when the condition is false\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Two-way selection statement\"]},\"A software development principle that stands for &#039;Don&#039;t Repeat Yourself&#039; which aims to reduce repetition in code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"DRY principle\"]},\"A keyword used to set the visibility of classes, variables, constructors, and methods\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Access modifier\"]},\"An object-oriented programming concept where the instance variables of a class are hidden from other classes and can be accessed only through the methods of the class\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Encapsulation\"]},\"A variable defined in a class that represents an attribute of an object\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Instance variable\"]},\"To improve the readability, reusability, or structure of program code without altering its functionality\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Refactor\"]},\"The first line of the constructor which includes the public keyword, the constructor name, and any parameters\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Constructor signature\"]},\"A predefined value that is used by a program when the user does not provide a value\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Default value\"]},\"A constructor with no parameters\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"No-argument constructor\"]},\"The value to assign to the formal parameter\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Actual parameter\"]},\"Copying the value of the actual parameter to the constructor&#039;s formal parameter\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Call by value\"]},\"The value to be passed to a constructor or method\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Formal parameter\"]},\"A variable declared and accessible within a specific block of code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Local variable\"]},\"Defining two or more constructors or methods with the same name but different signatures\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Overloading\"]},\"A constructor that has a specific number of arguments to be passed to assign values to an object&#039;s instance variables\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Parameterized constructor\"]},\"The attributes of an object that are represented by its instance variables\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"State\"]},\"Where a variable can be used\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Scope\"]},\"Using the assignment operator ( = ) to initialize or change the value stored in a variable\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Assignment\"]},\"Giving a starting value to a variable using the assignment operator ( = )\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Initialization\"]},\"A source code representation of a value, such as a number or text\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Literal\"]},\"A basic data type that Java predefines\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Primitive type\"]},\"A data type that contains a pointer to the memory location of an object\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Reference type\"]},\"Gives the value that is currently assigned to an instance variable\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Accessor method\"]},\"A library of prewritten classes\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Application program interface (API)\"]},\"A collection of methods or reusable components of code\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Library\"]},\"A copy of the value is given to where the method is called\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Return by value\"]},\"Shortcut syntax to perform an operation on both operands and assign the result into the variable on the left\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Compound assignment operator\"]},\"A combination of expressions\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Compound expression\"]},\"When two Strings are joined together\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Concatenation\"]},\"A combination of data and operators that evaluates to a single value\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Expression\"]},\"The data that is operated on\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Operand\"]},\"To cut off data from the end\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Truncate\"]},\"A logical statement that gives either a true or false value\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Boolean expression\"]},\"Changes the value assigned to an instance variable\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mutator method\"]},\"An operator used to compare values or expressions\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Relational operator\"]},\"Starts with a \\\\ to indicate how to display a String\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Escape sequence\"]},\"To define a method in a subclass with the same method signature as a method inherited from a superclass\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Override\"]},\"A structure for organizing, processing, retrieving, and storing data\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Data structure\"]},\"A single value or object in a data structure\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Element\"]},\"A data structure that holds multiple values of the same data type\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"One-dimensional (1D) array\"]},\"An integer value that indicates the position of a value in a data structure\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Index\"]},\"A comma-separated list of values or objects given inside curly braces ( { } )\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Initializer list\"]},\"To access elements in a data structure one by one\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Traverse\"]},\"To decrease a value by one\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Decrement\"]},\"To increase a value by one\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Increment\"]},\"A variable that is changed by a constant value and determines the end of a loop\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Loop control variable\"]},\"An error that occurs when a loop repeats one time too many or one time too few\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Off-by-one error\"]},\"A condition that must always be true just after the execution of a code segment\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Postcondition\"]},\"A condition that must always be true just before the execution of a code segment\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Precondition\"]},\"A file that contains letters, numbers, and\\/or symbols but has no special formatting\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Text file\"]},\"Where the same object or method has more than one form\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Polymorphism\"]},\"A loop inside of another loop\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nested loop\"]},\"A method that requires an object of the class to be created before it can be called\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Instance method\"]},\"A method that can be called without creating an object of the class\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Static method\"]},\"A variable that is shared by all instances of a class\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Static variable\"]},\"A variable whose value cannot be changed once it has been assigned\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Constant\"]},\"To assign a value of one type to another\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Cast\"]},\"Automatically cast from a smaller type to a larger type\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Widen\"]},\"A reference variable that points to the same object as another reference variable\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Alias\"]},\"A conditional statement nested inside of another conditional statement\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Nested conditional statement\"]},\"An expression using logical operators that evaluates to a Boolean value\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Compound Boolean expression\"]},\"A process in which the evaluation of a logical expression exits when the result is clear, even before the complete evaluation of the expression\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Short-circuited evaluation\"]},\"A table used to determine the truth values of a Boolean expression\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Truth table\"]},\"A set of rules that describe how to simplify complex Boolean expressions\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"De Morgan&#039;s Laws\"]},\"A statement that selects a single action from three or more conditional statements based on which Boolean expression is true\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Multi-selection statement\"]},\"A vertical (up and down) series of data in a two-dimensional (2D) array\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Column\"]},\"An array that is nested inside another array\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Inner array\"]},\"The outermost array of a two-dimensional array\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Outer array\"]},\"A horizontal (left to right) series of data in a two-dimensional (2D) array\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Row\"]},\"An array of arrays often represented as a table with rows and columns\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Two-dimensional (2D) array\"]},\"Traversing a 2D array by accessing each row from top to bottom\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Row-major order\"]},\"Traversing a 2D array by accessing each column from left to right\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Column-major order\"]},\"A color model consisting of red, green, and blue lights to display images\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"RGB\"]},\"The smallest unit of information in an image\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pixel\"]}}}', '[2,1,21]', 1);
INSERT INTO `decks` (`id`, `name`, `owner`, `data`, `viewdata`, `public`) VALUES
(54, 'Semester 1 English final', 'JeweledVessel39', '{\"desc\":\"does not include the questions of act 4 or 5 from Macbeth, not like you need them or anything\",\"contnt\":{\"the Germanic invasions\\u00a0\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Initiated the Renaissance in England\",\"Brought the language Anglo-Saxon, also called Old English, into England\",\"Destroyed the heroic ideal\",\"Are satirized in The Canterbury Tales\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"Anglo-Saxon culture and civilization\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Became the basis of the Normans\\u2019 whole way of life during the Germanic Invasion\",\"Became the basis of the Normans\\u2019 whole way of life during the Germanic Invasion - incorrectEmbraced beautiful artistic creation and a strong heroic ideal\",\"Was purely Christian, and had been cleansed of all pagan influences\",\"Celebrated the rediscovery of the Greek and Roman classics\",\"Ridiculed fate, which they called wyrd, as having no influence in their lives\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"Anglo-Saxon literature\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Included kennings, and used alliteration rather than rhyme\",\"Was often marked by an elegiac or heroic mood\",\"Was primarily oral, passed down from generation to generation\",\"Was created by scops, who recorded the deeds of the country\\u2019s various tribes or clans\",\"All of them\"],\"ans\":[4]},\"The language of the Anglo-Saxons\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Is very similar to English as we speak it today; it is easily understood\",\"Had very little artistic merit\",\"Is so different from our current English that it is like a foreign language\",\"Is also known as Norman French\",\"Lent itself to rhyming poetry, the most common form of Anglo-Saxon poetry\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"Which of the following is NOT an element of epic literature?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"An invocation to the muse, wherein the poet asks a god or goddess to inspire his poem\",\"Vast geographic spaces\",\"The hero always suffers a spectacular fall due to terrible flaws in his character\",\"A lofty tone, wherein all characters, horses, and even objects are given genealogies and honor\",\"The heroic ideal\"],\"ans\":[2]},\" An example of the elegiac mood in Beowulf  is when\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Unferth tells the story of a swimming match\",\"the poet mourns the death of Beowulf,  the kind of ruler he says we shall never see again\",\"Beowulf fights valiantly and rips Grendel\\u2019s arm off\",\"Hrothgar welcomes Beowulf and thanks him for his timely help\",\"the poet says that Grendel\\u2019s heart laughed when he sees the drunk and sleeping Danes\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"An example of the heroic mood in Beowulf  is when\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Unferth tells the story of a swimming match\",\"the poet mourns the passing of Beowulf, a ruler whose like we shall never see again\",\"Beowulf fights valiantly and rips Grendel\\u2019s arm off\",\"Hrothgar welcomes Beowulf and thanks him for his timely help\",\"the poet says that Grendel\\u2019s heart laughed when he sees the drunk and sleeping Danes\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"Grendel\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Defies Anglo-Saxon culture by hating music and gatherings, living in a swamp, and fighting unfairly\",\"Demonstrates the heroic trait of generosity\",\"Rips Unferth\\u2019s arm off and hangs it in Herot\",\"Lives alone, with no one to avenge his death\",\"Fights Beowulf bravely, with resolution and dignity, even though he\\u2019s a villain\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Beowulf\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Boasts publicly about past feats and about his plan to defeat Grendel without weapons\",\"Fails in his boast about Grendel and has to resort to using a sword\",\"Declines in his old age, unable to rid his kingdom of monsters, but does offer much wise council\",\"Comes from the same country as Unferth, Hrothgar and the other Danes\",\"Has little respect for the evil and incompetent Hrothgar\"],\"ans\":[0]},\" Unferth tells the story of a swimming match to\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"convince Hrthogar that Beowulf is capable of defeating Grendel\",\"embarrass Beowulf with one of his apparent failures in an attempted heroic adventure \",\"to explain why he himself will be victorious in killing Grendel\",\"to add another glory to the tales the scop will soon begin singing of Beowulf\",\"entertain these visiting Geats as they prepare for a night of battle\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"  Beowulf\\u2019s death\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"happens despite the bravery of the whole army that fiercely helps him fight the fire dragon\",\"is marked by the pity of this once astounding warrior decaying into weak, helpless old age\",\"results from his own greed\",\"was predicted by Hrothgar\",\"is marked by a fire to burn Beowulf\\u2019s body and destroy the gold he had wanted to give to his people\"],\"ans\":[4]},\" In \\u201cThe Seafarer,\\u201d the speaker\\u2019s attitude about his career as a sailor is best described asResponses\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"consistent pride and happiness\",\"a mixture of exhilaration versus lamentation about hardships\",\"steady discouragement at the hardships and the punishing sacrifices\",\"Christian scorn for adventure and a frustration that his sea journeys distracted him from what matters\",\"humorous embarrassment about some of the comic but human shames he suffered\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"After telling of his own life and feelings, the poet spends the last third of \\u201cThe Seafarer\\u201d\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"telling of other famous adventures he has heard the old scops speak of in heroic tales\",\"grieving for the family connections he lost when he was out at sea\",\"describing the beautiful home and satisfying family he returned to eventually\",\"warning others not to make the same career choice that he did\",\"judging one\\u2019s wealth as meaningless and declaring a godly life the only one worth living \"],\"ans\":[4]},\" The Norman Invasions\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Brought the rediscovered Greek and Roman classics into England\",\"Were resisted by King Arthur\",\"Were led by highly artistic people who did much to advance the poor state of art and learning in medieval England\",\"Brought French into England, which combined with Anglo-Saxon to make Middle English\",\"Started in 449 A.D.\"],\"ans\":[3]},\" In the film Becket, England experiences a conflict between\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Christians and rebellious nonbelievers\",\"The authority of the church and the power of the throne\",\"The Norman ruling class and the Anglo-Saxons they govern with scorn\",\"The lack of money and the need to help the peasant class\",\"Two of them\"],\"ans\":[4]},\"  One of Becket\\u2019s most driving hopes and goals, from the story\\u2019s start to finish, is to\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"understand where true honor comes from and to serve that honor himself\",\"bring down Henry in revenge for the death of his lover\",\"restore the dignity of the Normans, who are being oppressed and ridiculed by the ruling Saxons\",\"destroy England, a country he has little love for\",\"bring the power of God under the control of Henry and the nobles of England\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"As his true, underlying motive, Henry has himself whipped at the end of the film to\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"show his tragic guilt over what he has done to the Church\\u2019s power\",\"demonstrate his ability to survive the Church\\u2019s silly attempts to punish him\",\"show that he has finally given in to the Church and will bow his own power to God\\u2019s\",\"show that he has finally given in to the Church and will bow his own power to God\\u2019s - no response givenshow support for his friend Becket, whose death surprises Henry\",\"pretend that he is remorseful, so that he can gain the support of the common people again\"],\"ans\":[4]},\"In the middle ages, the church\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Was a divided institution due to the existence of so many competing denominations\",\"Was about the last place one would go for an education or to gain literacy\",\"Was as classist and sexist as the rest of society:  no poor person, and certainly no woman, could ever hope to hold an important position in it\",\"Exerted a profound influence on people\\u2019s daily lives through festivals and holidays, and over their whole life span through ceremonies like baptisms, weddings, and funerals\",\"Was served by a clergy who were always models of ethical perfection and right motives\"],\"ans\":[3]},\" Chaucer is considered the Father of English Poetry, or even the Father of English Literature, because he\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Invented all of his stories from scratch, rather than relying on the work of other authors\",\"Invented the epic and the Romance\",\"Was the first to use Middle English for artful poetry when French was still the language of the court\",\"Wrote Beowulf, England\\u2019s first great epic\",\"None of them\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"The practice of assessing a person&#039;s character or personality from their outer appearance  \":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Necromancy\",\"Astrology\",\"Physiognomy\",\"Psychology\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"  Which of the following is the most inappropriate in the Prioress\\u2019s role as a nun representing the church?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"She sings services and attends dinners\",\"Her rosary beads are like fancy jewelry and include a gold love charm on them\",\"She\\u2019s an Englishwoman who speaks French\",\"She tries hard to be polite\",\"Actually, she is a perfectly moral character with no flaws\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"The Wife of Bath\\u2019s lustful nature and love of flirting is symbolized in her \":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"scarlet hose\\u00a0\",\"gapped teeth\",\"holy relics\",\"red complexion\",\"three of them\"],\"ans\":[4]},\" The Parson  \":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"sells papers that free people from some of their summering in Hell or Purgatory\",\"uses information against people, threatening to embarrass them unless they give him money\",\"goes to fancy court dinners and his amazing table manner\",\"is a model of Christian virtue and cares deeply for his villagers\",\"wears fur-lined hoods and gowns and owns fine horses\"],\"ans\":[3]},\" The Monk\\u2019s bulging, excited eyes are a sign that he \":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"eats to much \",\"is an honest, devoted worker who serves God and man\",\"is a man of action, and not a meditative, thoughtful person\",\"is flirtatious and lustful\",\"is nervous and insecure\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"  The Summoner abuses his position when he\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"gives people summonses to church courts\",\"collects fake holy relics\",\"hunts, eats far too much, and wears fur clothing\",\"bribes people with their church summonses\",\"speaks Latin\"],\"ans\":[3]},\"  The first 20 or so lines of The Canterbury Tales describe, in great detail,      \":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"the pilgrims\",\"the town of Canterbury itself\",\"the vivid and exciting rebirth of nature in the spring\",\"Becket\\u2019s murder in Canterbury Cathedral, and it does so in long and violent detail\",\"how many stories each pilgrim will tell and what the topics must be\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"The moral of \\u201cThe Pardoner\\u2019s Tale\\u201d \":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Do unto others as you would have them do unto you\",\"Greed is the root of evil\",\"Man versus nature\",\"People in glass houses should not throw stones\",\"Judge not, lest ye be judged\"],\"ans\":[1]},\"Which of the following is NOT TRUE about pilgrimages?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Only the noble classes could afford to go on them\",\"They were one of the few ways women could travel without family\",\"They included destinations in England but also all over Europe and the Holy Lands\",\"The pilgrims who went on them represented a cross-section of all members and ranks of society\",\"Some people used them as one of the few opportunities to see the world beyond their own local life\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of a medieval romance?Responses\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"idealization of chivalry\",\"Idealization of the knight and his noble deeds\",\"Idealization of the knight&#039;s self-love\",\"Supernatural elements\",\"Imaginary or mystical settings\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"The play&#039;s first act wastes no time in giving us all of the following except:\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"an invasion\",\"some treacherous plotting\",\"an execution\",\"a cold-blooded murder\"],\"ans\":[3]},\"A brief opening scene gives us which of the following?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"a taste of the intrigue to come\",\"several key predictions\",\" humorous supernatural episode\",\"a foreboding view of the three influential characters\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Early in the play, we learn a number of important facts.  Which of the following is not one of them?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Duncan and Macbeth are brothers and merciless men\",\"Scotland was at war with an invader\",\"Duncan has a male heir named Malcolm\",\"The Thane of Cawdor is a traitor\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Before Macbeth makes his first appearance in the play, we learn about his\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"bravery\",\"great power\",\"superstitions\",\"ambition\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Macbeth&#039;s first reaction to the witches&#039; prediction is one of\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"wonderment\",\"indifference\",\"skepticism\",\"amusement\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"We soon learn not only that Macbeth is delighted at the thought of becoming king, but also that he\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"believes it can only happen openly and honorably\",\"assumes the witches will do all &quot;the dirty work&quot;\",\"hesitates to commit murder\",\"has many friends to help him become king\"],\"ans\":[2]},\"Lady Macbeth&#039;s remark that her husband is &quot;too full o&#039; the milk of human kindness&quot; indicates something about Macbeth&#039;s character, but it also reveals something about her.  She is\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"unambitious\",\"a\\u00a0treacherous half-Viking\",\"very much like her husband\",\"ruthless\"],\"ans\":[3]},\"In an actual stage performance of Macbeth, in Elizabethan times, Act One would require all of the following except:\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"elaborate stage props and frequent scene changes\",\"offstage musicians\",\"a trapdoor for the witches&#039; exit\",\"several players making entrances and exits\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"In Scene 1 of Act 2, Macbeth attempts to get Banquo to\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"kill the king&#039;s heirs\",\"oppose Duncan\",\"support him\",\"leave Scotland\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"When Macbeth is alone, he suffers from hallucinations and imagines he sees\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"a dagger\",\"Duncan&#039;s ghost\",\"a radiant crown\",\"an accusing hand\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"In Scene 2 Act 2, Lady Macbeth tells her husband that she\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"takes a full share in the murders\",\"feels weary and wishes to sleep\",\"thinks he should prepare a good alibi\",\"begins to regret the deeds\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"In scene 2 act 2, who sets the bloody daggers beside the murdered servants?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Lady Macbeth\",\"neither of them\",\"Macbeth\",\"both of them\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Shakespeare makes Duncan&#039;s murder seem more monstrous than it might have been by\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"always portraying the king in sympathetic terms\",\"making Duncan afraid of murder\",\"vividly describing the actual murder\",\"making the king disliked by his subjects\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"In scene 4 act 2, Macduff emphasizes his opposition to Macbeth by\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"refusing to go to Scone to see Macbeth crownedThis\",\"attempting to rally the thanes against Macbeth\",\"preparing to flee Scotland\",\"publicly swearing allegiance to Malcolm\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"As Scene 1 of Act 3 opens, Banquo reveals in a short soliloquy that he\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"suspects Macbeth killed Duncan\",\"hopes to keep peace with Macbeth\",\"wishes to leave Scotland\",\"is planning to kill Macbeth\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"Macbeth desires Banquo&#039;s death because he fears Banquo and because\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"the witches promised that Banquo would father kings\",\"Lady Macbeth wants Banquo killed\",\"Banquo opposes him at every turn\",\"Banquo is a friend of Donalbain\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"In the extended banquet scene, Macbeth chastises Banquo for being absent.  The irony of the speech lies in the fact that\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"Banquo is present in the form of a ghost\",\"the assembled lords are aware of Banquo&#039;s murder\",\"Banquo had no intention of attending the banquet\",\"Macbeth is unaware as yet of Banquo&#039;s death\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"At the banquet, Macbeth&#039;s tortured conscience causes him to\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"challenge Banquo&#039;s ghost\",\"drink excessively\",\"stagger out of the banquet hall\",\"confess the murder of Duncan\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"During the Banquet, Lady Macbeth does which of the following?\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"attempts to account to the guests for her husband&#039;s odd behavior\",\"sees the ghost also but manages to ignore it\",\"admits she fears for Macbeth&#039;s sanity\",\"confesses her own guilt to the assembled guests\"],\"ans\":[0]},\"In Scene 6 act 3, we learn that Macduff has gone to England to\":{\"type\":\"mc\",\"op\":[\"gather forces to depose Macbeth\",\"make peace with the English\",\"see his favorite son\",\"escape Macbeth&#039;s tyranny\"],\"ans\":[0]}}}', '[8,14,2,3,1]', 1),
(55, 'Classics - Paske Final Review Guide ', 'SeanO', '{\"desc\":\"For an overview of the whole study guide go here: https:\\/\\/docs.google.com\\/document\\/d\\/1D4SKlIe7RdFtBzeyQWX0IhzvIrT44RhFcreh0PxsjzQ\\/edit?tab=t.0\",\"contnt\":{\"Ancient Greek poet, traditionally credited with composing The Iliad and The Odyssey, which are foundational texts in Western literature.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Homer\"]},\"Legendary founder of Rome, along with his twin brother Remus, who is said to have established the city in 753 BCE.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Romulus\"]},\"A Greek playwright best known for his tragedies Oedipus Rex and Antigone, exploring themes of fate and human suffering.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sophocles\"]},\"Roman poet, author of The Aeneid, which tells the mythic origins of Rome through the hero Aeneas.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Vergil\"]},\"Roman general and statesman whose crossing of the Rubicon led to the fall of the Roman Republic and the rise of imperial Rome.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Julius Caesar\"]},\"First emperor of Rome, who established the Roman Empire and ushered in the Pax Romana (Roman Peace).\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Augustus\"]},\"Greek mathematician known as the &quot;father of geometry&quot; for his textbook Elements, which became a cornerstone of mathematics.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Euclid\"]},\"Greek playwright of comedies that satirized Athenian society and politics, such as Lysistrata and The Clouds.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aristophanes\"]},\"Roman emperor who legalized Christianity and founded the city of Constantinople, becoming a pivotal figure in the Christianization of the empire.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Constantine I\"]},\"Christian missionary whose letters (Epistles) and teachings were instrumental in spreading Christianity across the Roman Empire.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Paul of Tarsus\"]},\"Central figure of Christianity, believed by Christians to be the Son of God, whose life, death, and resurrection form the foundation of the faith.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jesus of Nazareth\"]},\"Greek mathematician and inventor, known for his work in geometry, physics, and engineering, including the Archimedean screw.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Archimedes\"]},\"Greek philosopher whose vast body of work in subjects ranging from ethics to biology shaped Western thought for centuries.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aristotle\"]},\"Philosopher known for his Socratic method of questioning, focusing on ethics and virtue, and influencing Western philosophy through the works of his student Plato.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Socrates\"]},\"Philosopher and student of Socrates, who wrote on justice, knowledge, and politics, with The Republic being his most influential work.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Plato\"]},\" The spread of Greek culture, language, and influence, especially during the conquests of Alexander the Great.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hellenize\"]},\"A key political institution in both the Roman Republic and Empire, where it initially held significant power before becoming more symbolic under the emperors.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Senate\"]},\"A period of relative peace and stability across the Roman Empire, lasting from 27 BCE to 180 CE, marked by economic prosperity and minimal internal conflict.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pax Romana\"]}}}', '[14,2,21,4,1]', 1),
(56, 'Medieval World - Paske Final Review Guide', 'SeanO', '{\"desc\":\"For an overview of the whole study guide go here: https:\\/\\/docs.google.com\\/document\\/d\\/1D4SKlIe7RdFtBzeyQWX0IhzvIrT44RhFcreh0PxsjzQ\\/edit?tab=t.0\",\"contnt\":{\" A Christian scholar and translator, best known for translating the Bible into Latin (the Vulgate), which became the standard version in the Western Christian world.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Saint Jerome\"]},\"A medieval Catholic philosopher and theologian, whose work Summa Theologica synthesized Christian doctrine with Aristotelian philosophy, shaping Catholic theology for centuries.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas Aquinas\"]},\"A theologian and philosopher whose writings, particularly Confessions and City of God, had a profound influence on Christian thought and Western philosophy.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Augustine of Hippo\"]},\"King of the Franks and Emperor of the Romans, who expanded the Carolingian Empire and played a key role in the Carolingian Renaissance, promoting education and Christian unity.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Charlemagne\"]},\"Byzantine emperor known for his ambitious legal reforms (the Corpus Juris Civilis), the construction of the Hagia Sophia, and efforts to reconquer parts of the former Western Roman Empire.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Justinian I\"]},\"A Kurdish Muslim leader who became the Sultan of Egypt and Syria, famous for his role in the Crusades, particularly his capture of Jerusalem from the Crusaders in 1187.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Saladin\"]},\"The first Norman King of England, who conquered England in 1066 at the Battle of Hastings and instituted Norman rule, drastically transforming English society and governance.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"William the Conqueror\"]},\"In Catholic doctrine, a temporary state of purification for souls who have died in grace but still need to be purified before entering heaven.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Purgatory\"]},\"Grants sold by the Church that offered remission from the temporal punishment for sins, often sold to raise funds for various Church projects, most controversially for the building of St. Peter&#039;s Basilica.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Indulgences\"]},\"The Muslim-ruled territories in the Iberian Peninsula (modern-day Spain and Portugal) from the 8th century until the fall of Granada in 1492, known for its cultural and intellectual flourishing.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"al-Andalus\"]},\"A physical object, typically associated with a saint or martyr, considered sacred in Christianity and often venerated as part of religious practice.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Relic\"]},\"A grant of land given by a lord to a vassal in exchange for military service or other obligations under the system of feudalism.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Fief\"]},\" A hierarchical system of land ownership and obligations that dominated medieval Europe, where lords granted land to vassals in exchange for loyalty, military service, and other duties.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Feudalism\"]},\"An economic system in medieval Europe where peasants worked the land on manors (large estates) owned by lords, in exchange for protection and the right to live on the land.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Manorialism\"]},\"The head of the Roman Catholic Church, considered the spiritual leader of all Catholics and the successor to Saint Peter, holding significant religious and political influence in medieval Europe.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pope\"]},\"Members of religious orders (such as monks and nuns) who follow a specific rule (regula), living in communities and focusing on prayer, work, and contemplation.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Regular Clergy\"]},\"Priests, bishops, and other clergy who live in the world, outside of monastic life, often serving in parishes, administering sacraments, and overseeing religious duties for laypeople.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Secular Clergy\"]},\"Religious rites in Christianity considered essential for spiritual growth and salvation, such as baptism, Eucharist, confession, and marriage.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sacraments\"]}}}', '[14,2,21]', 1),
(57, 'Early Modern Europe - Paske Final Review Guide', 'SeanO', '{\"desc\":\"For an overview of the whole study guide go here: https:\\/\\/docs.google.com\\/document\\/d\\/1D4SKlIe7RdFtBzeyQWX0IhzvIrT44RhFcreh0PxsjzQ\\/edit?tab=t.0\",\"contnt\":{\"An Italian architect and engineer, best known for designing the dome of the Florence Cathedral, a masterpiece of Renaissance architecture.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Filippo Brunelleschi\"]},\"A Renaissance painter and architect, known for his harmonious and balanced compositions, such as The School of Athens and numerous Madonna paintings.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Raphael\"]},\"Renowned sculptor, painter, and architect, famous for works like the David statue, the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel, and designing St. Peter\\u2019s Basilica in Rome.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Michelangelo\"]},\"A polymath of the Renaissance, renowned for his art (such as The Last Supper and Mona Lisa), scientific studies, and engineering inventions.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Leonardo da Vinci\"]},\"A Dutch humanist, theologian, and scholar who advocated for reform within the Catholic Church and emphasized education and classical learning.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Desiderius Erasmus\"]},\"An English humanist and statesman, author of Utopia, a work that critiques contemporary society and imagines an ideal, just community.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas More\"]},\"An influential Italian statesman and patron of the arts, he was a key figure in the Medici family, supporting Renaissance artists and thinkers like Leonardo and Michelangelo.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lorenzo de Medici\"]},\"A Portuguese explorer who was the first to reach India by sea, opening the maritime route to Asia and greatly expanding European influence in the East.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Vasco da Gama\"]},\"An Italian explorer whose voyages, sponsored by Spain, led to the European discovery of the Americas in 1492.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Christopher Columbus\"]},\"A Spanish conquistador who led the conquest of the Aztec Empire in modern-day Mexico, claiming vast territories for Spain.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hern\\u00e1n Cort\\u00e9s\"]},\"A German theologian and key figure in the Protestant Reformation, he famously nailed his 95 Theses to the church door in 1517, criticizing Catholic practices like indulgences.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Martin Luther\"]},\"An English theologian and reformer who criticized the Catholic Church\\u2019s corruption and advocated for the translation of the Bible into English.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"John Wycliffe\"]},\"King of England, known for his role in the English Reformation, particularly for breaking from the Catholic Church to form the Church of England after his dispute over his marriage to Catherine of Aragon.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Henry VIII\"]},\"A Catholic religious order founded by Ignatius of Loyola, focused on education, missionary work, and supporting the Counter-Reformation.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jesuits\"]},\"A radical Christian movement during the Reformation, advocating for adult baptism and a separation of church and state, often facing persecution from both Catholics and Protestants.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Anabaptists\"]},\"The exchange of plants, animals, diseases, and cultures between the Old World and the New World following Christopher Columbus&#039; voyages.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Columbian Exchange\"]},\"An economic theory dominant in Europe from the 16th to 18th centuries, emphasizing the accumulation of wealth through trade, colonial expansion, and state intervention in the economy.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Mercantilism\"]},\"A practice in which wealthy individuals, families, or institutions supported artists, writers, and scholars, often during the Renaissance, in exchange for commissions or favor.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Patronage System\"]},\"A political treatise by Niccol\\u00f2 Machiavelli, advising rulers on how to maintain power through pragmatism and realpolitik, famously asserting that &quot;the ends justify the means.&quot;\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"The Prince\"]},\"A term used to describe European rulers in the late 15th and early 16th centuries, such as Ferdinand and Isabella of Spain, who centralized power, reduced feudal influences, and strengthened royal authority.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"New Monarchs\"]}}}', '[14,2,21,1]', 1);
INSERT INTO `decks` (`id`, `name`, `owner`, `data`, `viewdata`, `public`) VALUES
(58, 'English S1 Study Guide', 'JBR33ZY', '{\"desc\":\"\",\"contnt\":{\"The story that marks the beginning of English literature; profoundly human\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Beowulf\"]},\"This language has extensive and imaginative vocabulary, allowing the speaker to transmit strong images; powerful not privative; influenced by language of Romans, Angles, Saxons, and Jutes; largely Germaning (related to modern German and Dutch)\\u00a0\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Old English\"]},\"Unlike Modern English, Old English was primarily a ___ language\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"spoken\",\"oral\"]},\"After Romans leave England due to weakness, these three tribes take over\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Jutes, Saxons, Angles\",\"Jutes Saxons Angles\"]},\"Courage, valor, loyalty, courtesy, and generosity are all admired traits of the ___\\u00a0\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Anglo-Saxons\",\"Anglo Saxons\"]},\"A professional poet and musician who served as the memory and historian of the tribe; it was he who remembered important heroes, kings, battles, and tribe folklore\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Scop\"]},\"A  compressed compound expression with metaphorical meaning;\\nan object is described in a two-word phrase, such as &#039;whale-road&#039; for \\u2018sea.\\u2019 \":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Kenning\"]},\"Person likely behind The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle (first historical record in English); responsible for translations of biblical texts and other intellectually complicated writings\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Alfred the Great\"]},\"Believed the education of his subjects was necessary-especially the teaching of writing and reading; established the first public schools in England; formulated a code of law\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Alfred the Great\"]},\"St. Augustine\\u2019s influence on King Ethelbert of Kent sparked a rebirth of ___ in England\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Christianity\\u00a0\"]},\"The most learned and industrious writer of the Anglo-Saxon Period; Author of A History of the English Church and People (written in Latin);\\nRegarded as \\u201cthe father of English history\\u201d\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Venerable Bede\",\"Bede\"]},\"First Archbishop of Canterbury\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"St. Augustine\"]},\"First English religious poet\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Caedmon\"]},\"Traditions that describe the feats of great heros\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Heroic Traditions\",\"Heroic\"]},\"Traditions that mourn the passing of earlier, better times\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Elegiac Traditions\",\"Elegiac\"]},\"A long, narrative poem recounting heroic deeds against a background of war and the supernatural; examples: Iliad, Odyssey, Aeneid, Paradise Lost\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Epic Poem\",\"Epic\"]},\"___\\u00a0is considered a folk epic which describes early ideals, characteristics, and traditions of a people or nation; ___, the hero is the best introduction we have to the ideals and beliefs of the Anglo-Saxons. He shows us the way of life they admired, idealized, and attempted to emulate.\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Beowulf\"]},\"This date is when England was lost to the Romans and the English tribes took over\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"449\"]},\"This date marks the Norman conquest of England during the Battle of Hastings; led the mix of Anglo-Saxon and French culture\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"1066\"]},\"A formalized boast; functions as a traditional aspect of Anglo-Saxon culture and a conventional, stylized feature of their poetry\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Gielp\",\"Yelp\"]},\"A short, emotional poem which focuses on deep feelings or thoughts; expresses deep personal emotions.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lyric Poem\",\"Lyric\"]},\"This battle took place in 1066 when\\u00a0William of Normandy invaded England and defeated King Harold, taking the throne that he claimed was promised to him.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Battle of Hastings\"]},\"These people contributed administrative, legal, and adaptive abilities after 1066\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Normans\"]},\"These people\\u00a0contributed a fairly democratic governing process, artistic ability, and sensibility after 1066\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Anglo-Saxons\",\"Anglo Saxons\"]},\"This was an inventory of property throughout England that was drawn up at William the Conqueror\\u2019s command; helped settle property disputes and led to more                                 equitable taxation\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Domesday Book\"]},\"As the ___ industry grew more and more common, people became wage earners and a merchant class grew up\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Wool\"]},\"law based on custom and usage, which applies uniformly across class lines to all members of a society\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Common Law\"]},\"Process of ascertaining guilt or innocence by giving an accused person tasks to perform, successful completion of which means his or her innocence\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ordeal\"]},\"law which gives the firstborn son the father\\u2019s property and titles upon his death\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Law of Primogeniture\"]},\"a charter signed by King John in 1215; it states that the king could not levy taxes without the consent of the barons.  It foreshadowed many important legal rights, such as representative government\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Magna Carta\"]},\"The king who signed the Magna Carta\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"King John\"]},\"The date for the signing of the Magna Carta\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"1215\"]},\"Knowledge of mathematics and medicine, refinements of living, broadened trade horizons, and the concept of chivalry were all affects of the what?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Crusades\"]},\"The period of time which the Crusades took place during\\u00a0\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"1095-1289\"]},\"England fought a series of wars attempting to hold its French possessions, but was ultimately driven from France\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"100 Years War\",\"Hundred Years War\"]},\"Civil war between the Houses of York and Lancaster (1455-1485).  Henry VII united the feuding families by marriage and began the Tudor line of monarchs\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"War of the Roses\"]},\"The two English houses that fought during the War of the Roses\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"York, Lancaster\",\"York Lancaster\",\"York and Lancaster\"]},\"Idealizing Chivalry, noble hero-knights, and women, imaginative, vast, fairytale-like settings, and supernatural elements are all characteristics of\\u00a0 ___\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Medieval Romance\"]},\"___, or oral songs and poems, came from the common people of Scotland and England.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Ballads\"]},\"This type of medieval play\\u00a0entertained crowds with comic characters portraying wicked characters, such as the Devil.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Miracle Play\",\"Miracle Plays\"]},\"This type of medieval play was more elaborate, allegorical presentations in which characters represented virtues and vices.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Morality Play\",\"Morality Plays\"]},\"Pioty, penance, quest for healing, and adventure were all reasons individuals would go on ___\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Pilgrimage\"]},\"He was the only truly great writer of the period, in fact, the first in English history.  His poetic and humorous realism were also firsts in the medieval diet of anonymous storytelling by the scops.\\n\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Geoffrey Chaucer\",\"Chaucer\"]},\"A storytelling device in which one story provides the organization of and structure for a second tale or a series of tales\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Frame story\"]},\"(from the Greek physis meaning nature and gnomon meaning \\u201cjudge\\u201d or \\u201cinterpret\\u201d) The practice of assessing a person&#039;s character or personality from their outer appearance\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Physiognomy\"]},\"A comparison made between two things through the use of a specific word of comparison, such as like, as, than, or resembles\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Simile\"]},\"A contrast or an incongruity between what is stated and what is really meant, or between what is expected to happen and what actually happens\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Irony\"]},\"A kind of writing that holds up to ridicule or contempt the weaknesses and wrong-doings of individuals, groups, institutions, or humanity in general\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Satire\"]},\"two consecutive and rhyming lines of verse written in iambic pentameter (heroic)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Heroic Couplet\"]},\"____________ is an example of a frame story or frame tale, which employs a unifying \\u201cframe\\u201d or story within which one or more tales are related. In the single story, the opening and closing constitutes a frame. In the cyclical frame story\\u2014that is, a story in which several tales are related\\u2014some frames are externally imposed and only loosely bind the diversified stories.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Canterbury Tales\"]},\"Hint, insinuation; especially: a veiled suggestion concerning character or reputation\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Innuendo\"]},\"a general truth briefly expressed\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Maxim\"]},\"A rhetorical device defined as a short tale, narrative, or anecdote (a short, amusing, or interesting story about an incident or a person) used in literary pieces and speeches to explain doctrine or to emphasize a moral point\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Exemplum\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Which character begins as a loyal general but becomes consumed by ambition, leading to his downfall?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Macbeth\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who manipulates Macbeth by questioning his masculinity?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lady Macbeth\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What title does Macbeth hold before becoming king?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thane of Glamis\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who is described as &quot;too full o&#039; the milk of human kindness&quot;?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Macbeth\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who serves as a foil to Macbeth by remaining loyal and honorable?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Banquo\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who is the first character to openly suspect Macbeth of murder?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Macduff\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Which character becomes a vengeful force after the murder of his family?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Macduff\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who escapes Macbeth\\u2019s attempt to murder him and becomes a threat to Macbeth\\u2019s rule?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Fleance\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Which character provides comic relief after Duncan\\u2019s murder?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Porter\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who is described as &quot;not born of woman&quot; in the prophecy?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Macduff\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What vision appears to Macbeth before Duncan&#039;s murder?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A dagger\",\"Dagger\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What unnatural event occurs the night of Duncan\\u2019s murder?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Eclipse\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What does Lady Macbeth obsessively do to symbolize her guilt?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Wash her hands\",\"Wash hands\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What is Banquo promised by the witches?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"A line of kings\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0How does Lady Macbeth die?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Suicide\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What excuse does Lady Macbeth give for Macbeth\\u2019s strange behavior at the banquet?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"An illness\",\"illness\",\"he is ill\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What title is bestowed upon Macbeth by King Duncan before the murder?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thane of Cawdor\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0What is Lady Macduff\\u2019s criticism of her husband before her death?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"He abandoned his family\",\"abandonment\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0Who leads the army against Macbeth in the final act?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Malcolm\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Look like the innocent flower, but be the serpent under\\u2019t.&quot;\\u2014Who says this?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Lady Macbeth\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Will all great Neptune\\u2019s ocean wash this blood clean from my hand?&quot;\\u2014What does this line symbolize?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Guilt\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Life\\u2019s but a walking shadow, a poor player...&quot;\\u2014What does this speech reveal about Macbeth\\u2019s view on life?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Life is meaningless\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Double, double, toil and trouble...&quot;\\u2014Who chants this line?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Witches\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Thou shalt get kings, though thou be none.&quot;\\u2014Who is this prophecy about?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Banquo\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Out, damned spot!&quot;\\u2014What does Lady Macbeth refer to in this line?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Duncan&#039;s Blood\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;There\\u2019s daggers in men\\u2019s smiles.&quot;\\u2014Who says this line?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Donalbain\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;If chance will have me king, why, chance may crown me.&quot;\\u2014What does this line reflect about Macbeth\\u2019s mindset?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Hesitation\"]},\"(MACBETH)\\u00a0&quot;Macbeth shall never vanquished be until Great Birnam Wood to high Dunsinane Hill shall come against him.&quot;\\u2014What literary device is used in this prophecy?\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Irony\"]},\"The period of European history and culture traditionally known as the ___ began in Italy during the fourteenth century and extended, in England at least, past the middle of the seventeenth century.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Renaissance\"]},\"This period (Renaissance) revitalized interest in ___ and ___ civilizations.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Greek; Roman\",\"Greek, Roman\",\"Greek Roman\"]},\"Scholars and educators who called themselves ___ began to emphasize the capacities of the human mind and the achievements of human culture, in contrast to the medieval emphasis on God and contempt for the things of the world\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Humanists\"]},\"During the fifteenth, the great period in Italy did not expand to England because of the terrible internal turmoil and instability caused by the ___, a battle for the throne between Yorks and Lancasters\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"War of the Roses\"]},\"The author of Utopia\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Thomas More\"]},\"Thomas More&#039;s ___ may be thought of as the first literary masterpiece of the English period of literary and artistic rebirth\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Utopia\"]},\"The movement of religious protest against the authority and corruption of the Roman Catholic Church had been simmering for several years. This movement, known as the ___, was fiercely accelerated with the actions of Martin Luther\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Protestant Reformation\",\"Reformation\"]},\"On the death of Henry VII, ___ took the throne and was ideally equipped to encourage those literary and artistic developments that would finally allow literary and artistic development to grow and flourish\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Elizabeth I\",\"Elizabeth\"]},\"The greatest and most distinctive achievement of the Elizabethan literature is in ___\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"drama\"]},\"The most striking feature of the Elizabethan artistic taste is a delight in elaborate pattern and complicated ornamentation known as ___\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"artifice\"]},\"Elizabethans saw the world as a vast, unified, hierarchical order, or ____________, in which every existing being or thing was ranked within a category along a vertical spectrum\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Great Chain of Being\"]},\"In the __________, each member of a group corresponded to same-ranking members of other groups. Thus gold was analogous to oak. This Elizabethan writers had at hand a wealth of symbolic relationships, references, and allusions.\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Doctrine of Correspondence\"]},\"During the Jacobean era, ___ ruled his\\/her kingdom of Scotland together with that of England until 1625\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"James I\"]},\"___ took the power of the English government into his own hands and established what he called the Protectorate (a military dictatorship that did not endure for very long)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Oliver Cromwell\"]},\"By 1660, the English people had had enough of the ___ rule, and ___ returned to the throne in what is called the ___ (yes, there are 3 answers)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Protectorate; Charles II; Restoration\",\"Protectorate, Charles II, Restoration\",\"Protectorate Charles II Restoration\"]},\"___ poetry extends the Elizabethan love of intricate verbal construction and feeling for dramatic voice and situation (it is more argumentative in tone); its language is more colloquial; its meter is usually varied (depends on the combination of dissimilar images)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Metaphysical\"]},\"The major style or approach to poetry in the seventeenth century was classical and conservative, ___ poetry; the poems of this variety are light, witty, and elegant, yet they retain an emphasis on fineness and precision of form\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Cavalier\"]},\"means \\u201crebirth\\u201d of the artistic and intellectual energies that characterized Greek and Roman culture\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Renaissance\"]},\"a devoted classical scholar and poet. \\rConsidered the \\u201cfather of humanism\\u201d\\r\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Petrarch\"]},\"belief that the church should only control spiritual matters, not science or civic matters; and that individuals should control their own destiny. Classical rhetoric, literature, and philosophy is emphasized\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Humanism\"]},\"The date when Henry Tudor defeated the Yorkist King Richard III established the Tudor dynasty (ruled for more than a century)\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"1485\"]},\"a fourteen-line poem written in iambic pentameter (each line contains ten syllables, five of which are usually stressed. The word comes from Italian, meaning \\u201clittle sound\\u201d or \\u201clittle song.\\u201d\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sonnet\"]},\"More popular with modern readers - energy and expressiveness of his verses;\\ra diplomat for Henry VIII;\\radapted European forms and ideas to English poetry;\\rtranslated Petrarch\\u2019s poems, credited with introducing England to the sonnet\\r\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sir Thomas Wyatt\",\"Thomas Wyatt\"]},\"Called \\u201cthe poet\\u2019s poet\\u201d because of his influence on later poets;\\rthe greatest non-dramatic poet of the Elizabethan Age; \\rBecame attached to the Earl of Leicester, Queen Elizabeth\\u2019s favorite nobleman;\\rbecame friends with Philip Sidney\\r\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Edmund Spenser\",\"Spenser\"]},\"Embodiment of the ideal Renaissance man: courtier, diplomat, casual man of letters,\\rdeepest interests were political and religious; Uncle was Robert Dudley, Earl of Leicester \\r\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Sir Philip Sidney\",\"Philip Sidney\",\"Sidney\"]},\"figure of speech personifying an abstract idea, dead or absent person, or non-living object by addressing it as if a real and present person\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"apostrophe\"]},\"a dramatic convention in which a character turns \\u201caside\\u201d to speak a few words directly to the audience of to another character, but is not supposed to be heard by others on the stage\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Aside\"]},\"verse written in unrhymed iambic pentameter\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Blank Verse\"]},\"a dramatic convention in which a character makes an extended speech while alone on the stage\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Soliloquy\"]},\"an event or a detail that is chronologically out of its proper time in history\":{\"type\":\"txt\",\"ans\":[\"Anachronism\"]}}}', '[9,14,19,2,21,4,24,22]', 1),
